  <span id="freeText15794987324219214185" style="display:none">This gets five full-blown stars this time around. The full wickedness of the book's title is only understood after reading. Faulkner set out to write the most scandalous, shocking, filthy book he could, for $ purposes. He succeeds at this but the book is still a work of art. The characters can be split into two camps, those with a moral compass and those without. Those with (poor Horace) are bound to be disappointed, by the world and by themselves. But each unhappy person is unhappy in his own way, so with Temple--consumed by earthly desires--and with Popeye--who was shut out from ever experiencing them (chiefly sex, booze, in "Sanctuary" the bases of friendship, love) from childhood. They are cursed in opposite manners. Also running throughout is the association of femininity with springtime, hardly a new development, but here Faulkner treats both as something strangely sinister and even filthy (think Mr. Compson's talk in "The Sound and the Fury"). It's bizarre and unsettling and at minimum achieves the aforementioned purpose of unsettlement, but something more too...thoughts?<br /><br />(3/4/16)<br /><br />NOTES FROM FIRST READING:<br /><br />-The writing isn't up to Faulkner's wickedly high standards, but it's still better than most anything else. Had F taken the time to revise it before cashing in it would be seen as equal to his prior two by lit types.<br />-Many point out the book's bleakness but like the high tragedies F drew from it is not without comic relief. An episode of two townfolk unwittingly staying in a Memphis brothel stands out.<br />-Unfortunately the naming here is a little cute. Narcisa, the self-absorbed sister, Temple Drake, she whose purity is profaned and ransacked, etc.<br />-Dogs do not "scrabble" across the floor, Bill. Stop saying that.<br />-F seemed to get bored towards the end which is a shame cuz the courtroom scenes, which could have been great, were heavily abridged.<br />-The reader can see why F was a good choice to adapt "The Big Sleep" to the big screen. Horace is a sad man playing Philip Marlowe.<br />-Fun fact: the first film adaptation of "Sanctuary", retitled "The Story of Temple Drake", was among the most cited films as evidence for the necessity of what would come to be the Hays Code.<br />-Joseph Conrad's influence also obvious in certain dialogue-nested monologues.<br />-The most scandalous monologue is Temple's to Horace, but it feels like a flacid attempt to recreate Addie Bundren's chapter in As I Lay Dying. The best go to Horace who sounds literally exactly like the narrator, which in this author's case aint bad.<br /><br />(10/31/14)</span>
