  <span id="freeText5108657693088973468" style="display:none">Not sure this was the best starting place for my reading of Faulkner, but certainly it’s the sort of plot that attracts me. <br />It begins with lawyer Horace Benbow fleeing his wife and even more, his stepdaughter, with whose budding sexuality he is become obsessed. On the way to his sister’s house, he encounters a decaying plantation being run as a bootlegging site by Lee Goodwin. Goodwin lives with his long-suffering mistress, Ruby Lamar, and their baby, who sleeps in a box behind the stove to avoid the rats, along with the mentally challenged Tommy. Last, but by no means least, there is the menacing, mysterious, and almost inhuman Popeye, whom Benbow meets and at once has an hour long staring contest. Alcoholic Gowan Stevens, seeking booze, arrives on the scene with 18 year old student Temple Drake; crashes his car, and the couple is forced to stay among the bootleggers. <br />What follows is a ruthless, unsparing description of a decaying society, with Benbow pitched against what is largely a group of amoral fiends. <br />Controversial with its descriptions of sexual violence, but never exploitative, I can imagine the impact this must have had on publication in 1931. The author’s explanation of the behaviour of his characters appears to be that they have been socially conditioned by their environment, though the title appears wholly inappropriate, but perhaps ironic; there is at no time any sanctuary. <br />I found it fascinating. <br /></span>
